<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910830-0062</DOCNO><DOCID>910830-0062.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Officials Convicted   Of Charges Connected   With Thrift's Collapse</HL><DATE>08/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ST. PAUL, Minn. -- A federal jury here convicted fourformer executives of Midwest Federal Savings andamp; Loan onnumerous felony charges stemming from its collapse in 1989.   The court acquitted the four on some counts, but all wereconvicted of the most serious charge of racketeering.</LP><TEXT>   Guilty verdicts were handed down against Hal Greenwood,former chairman, who was found guilty on 25 of the 27charges, including conspiracy, several securities fraudcounts, misapplication of funds, filing false reports togovernment regulators and racketeering. Mr. Greenwood'sdaughter, Susan Greenwood Olson, a former vice president atMidwest, was convicted on 11 of 12 counts.   Also, Charlotte Masica, former managing officer, wasconvicted on 13 of 21 charges; and Robert A. Mampel, formersenior vice president at Midwest and a former Minnesota statebanking commissioner, was convicted on 14 of 15 counts.   U.S. Attorney Jerry Arnold said Mr. Greenwood and theother defendants &quot;were profiting from huge bonuses whileMidwest was rotting away financially.&quot; He said the defendantsmanipulated financial records and made unsafe loans toconceal millions of dollars from federal regulators.   The racketeering count carries a sentence of as much as 20years, and most of the other counts have maximum sentences offive years.</TEXT></DOC>